We use the notation of \cite{ha} and \cite{htt} without change. We make heavy use of the theory of $\infty$-operads therein, and refer to \cite{ha} for a full description of that theory or \cite{beardscomod} for a brief review. For the extent of this note all Kan complexes will have base points and all maps between them will be basepoint preserving. We will denote the quasicategory of such objects by ${\mathcal{T}}$. We will denote the stabilization of ${\mathcal{T}}$, the quasicategory of spectra, by ${\mathcal{S}}$. It has a symmetric monoidal structure with unit object the sphere spectrum ${\mathbb{S}}$. In certain cases we will need our connected Kan complexes to be \emph{reduced}, i.e. have a unique 0-simplex, but when this occurs we will say so.

\begin{defi}\label{quotient}
Let $i:H\to G$ be a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal Kan complexes. Define the quotient of $G$ by $H$, denoted $G/H$, to be the relative tensor product $G\otimes_H\ast$ in the sense of 4.4.2 of \cite{ha}, where the $H$-module structure on $G$ is determined by $i$. Recall that as the cone point of an operadic colimit diagram $G/H$ admits a universal morphism $q:G\to G/H$. Note that $i$ is not made explicit in the notation, but will always be clear from context.
\end{defi}

\begin{lem}\label{structuredquot}
If $i:H\to G$ is a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal Kan complexes then $G/H$ is an ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complex and the quotient morphism $q:G\to G/H$ is a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complexes.
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
