 One important distinction to make between this work and earlier work on Hopf-Galois extensions of ring spectra is that the work of Rognes and Roth relies on the theory of model categories introduced by Quillen \cite{quillha}, whereas \cite{beardscomod} uses the theory of quasicategories introduced originally by Boardman and Vogt \cite{boardvogt} and elaborated upon by Joyal \cite{joyalapps} and Lurie \cite{htt} \cite{ha}. A great deal of work has been done by the latter author to ensure that Quillen's theory of model categories maps faithfully to the theory of quasicategories and that both frameworks are useful for doing homotopy theory.

\section{Background}

We use the notation of \cite{ha} and \cite{htt} without change. We make heavy use of the theory of $\infty$-operads therein, and refer to \cite{ha} for a full description of that theory or \cite{beardscomod} for a brief review. For the extent of this note all Kan complexes will have base points and all maps between them will be basepoint preserving. We will denote the quasicategory of such objects by ${\mathcal{T}}$. We will denote the stabilization of ${\mathcal{T}}$, the quasicategory of spectra, by ${\mathcal{S}}$. It has a symmetric monoidal structure with unit object the sphere spectrum ${\mathbb{S}}$. In certain cases we will need our connected Kan complexes to be \emph{reduced}, i.e. have a unique 0-simplex, but when this occurs we will say so.

\begin{defi}\label{quotient}
Let $i:H\to G$ be a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal Kan complexes. Define the quotient of $G$ by $H$, denoted $G/H$, to be the relative tensor product $G\otimes_H\ast$ in the sense of 4.4.2 of \cite{ha}, where the $H$-module structure on $G$ is determined by $i$. Recall that as the cone point of an operadic colimit diagram $G/H$ admits a universal morphism $q:G\to G/H$. Note that $i$ is not made explicit in the notation, but will always be clear from context.
\end{defi}

\begin{lem}\label{structuredquot}
If $i:H\to G$ is a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal Kan complexes then $G/H$ is an ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complex and the quotient morphism $q:G\to G/H$ is a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complexes.
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
To construct $G/H$ as an ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complex, we first notice that the relative bar construction of Section 4.4 of \cite{ha} is constructed from the data of modules over an ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-algebra and that $Alg_{{\mathbb{E}}_n}({\mathcal{T}})\simeq Alg_{{\mathbb{E}}_1}(Alg_{{\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}}({\mathcal{T}}))$. In other words the operadic bar construction of Construction 4.4.2.7 of \cite{ha} is relative to the operad $\mathcal{O}^\otimes\simeq {\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}^\otimes$ and $Bar_\bullet(G,H,\ast)$ is a simplicial object of $Alg_{{\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}}({\mathcal{T}})$. As the forgetful functor $Alg_{{\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}}({\mathcal{T}})\to {\mathcal{T}}$ is ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal it preserves the relevant structure in $G/H=G\otimes_H\ast$ and the map it receives from $G\times\ast\simeq G$. 
\end{proof}

Recall from \cite{beardscomod} that if $H$ is a cocommutative bialgebra in ${\mathcal{S}}$ (with an ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-algebra structure for some $n$), the quasicategory of $H$-comodules admits a symmetric monoidal structure. Moreover, since $H$ is a bialgebra and admits a unit ${\mathbb{S}}\to H$, there is a \emph{trivial comodule} functor ${\mathcal{S}}\to Comod_H$ which takes a spectrum $A$ to the comodule with comodule structure map $A\simeq A\otimes {\mathbb{S}}\to A\otimes H$. We will say that an $H$-comodule \emph{is a trivial $H$-comodule} if it is in the essential image of this functor.

\begin{rem}\label{diffcoaction}
Let $H$ be a cocommutative ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-bialgebra in ${\mathcal{S}}$, and let $B$ be an ${\mathbb{E}}_m$-algebra in $CoMod_H$. Then the comodule structure map $c:B\to B\otimes H$ gives $B\otimes H$ the structure of a an ${\mathbb{E}}_k$-$B$-algebra, for $k=\mathrm{min}(n,m)$. On the other hand the trivial coaction $B\simeq B\otimes {\mathbb{S}}\to B\otimes H$ induces a different $B$-algebra structure on $B\otimes H$ which corresponds to the map $B\otimes B\otimes H\overset{\mu_B\otimes 1_H}\to B\otimes H$.
\end{rem}

