\begin{lem}\label{univquot}
Given a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complexes $G\to X$ such that the $H$-module structure on $X$ induced by the composition $H\overset{i}\to G\to X$ is the trivial $H$-module structure, there is a factorization $G\to G/H\to X$ and a natural equivalence of functors between $G\to G/H\to X$ and $G\to X$. 
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
The quotient $G/H$ is constructed as the relative tensor product ${G\otimes_H \ast}$ (see Definition \ref{quotient}). By using the ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-$H$-algebra structure of $G$ and $\ast$ (since $G$ and $H$ both receive ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal morphisms from $H$), we can construct $G/H$ as a bar construction in ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-$H$-algebras (as in Theorem 4.4.2.8 of \cite{ha}). Since the $H$-action on $X$ is trivial and is induced by the composition $H\to G\to X$, the morphism  $G\to X$ then defines a morphism from the simplicial object defining $G/H$ into the constant simplicial object on $X$. Or, in other words, there is a coherently $H$-bilinear morphism $G\otimes_H\ast\to X$ essentially coming from the commutative diagram

where the upper horizontal map and the left-hand vertical map are the $H$-action on $G$ and the unit of $H$, respectively, and the other maps are the given map $G\to X$.  Thus by the universal property of the colimit (again being taken within ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complexes) the needed factorization is obtained.
\end{proof}

\section{Examples}\label{examples}

A large number of morphisms of ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal Kan complexes  fit into the framework described in the introduction and Theorem \ref{mainthm}. We assume that a morphism of connected $n$-fold loop spaces is always modeled by a morphism of reduced ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal Kan complexes. The following Lemma allows us to positively identify such examples.
\begin{prop}\label{fibs}
Let $F\to E$ be a morphism of connected ${\mathbb{E}}_n$-monoidal Kan complexes for $n\geq 1$ and let $X$ be the ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal fiber of the induced ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-morphism $BF\to BE$. Then $F\to E\to X$ satisfies the conditions of  Theorem \ref{mainthm}. In particular $X$ is equivalent to $E/F$ as an ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complex.
\end{prop}

\begin{proof}
The universal property of $E/F$ (cf. Lemma \ref{univquot}) induces a morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-monoidal Kan complexes $E/F\to X$, which induces an equivalence on underlying Kan complexes (see also Proposition 8.8 of \cite{mayclassfib}). 
\end{proof}

