\subsection{A New Construction of $MU$}

In the case that $G/H$ is equivalent to $S^n$ for some finite $n$, Theorem 4.10 of \cite{acb} and Theorem \ref{mainthm} above allow us to give more concrete constructions of Hopf-Galois extensions as versal ${\mathbb{E}}_{n-1}$-algebras (see e.g. \cite{szymikprimechar} and \cite{acb} for more on this). In fact, this type of characterization follows just from Proposition \ref{factorization}, as the cofixed points condition of Hopf-Galois extensions is unnecessary.  One example that may be of particular interest to stable homotopy theorists is a construction of ${M\mathrm{U}}$ as a canonical sequence of Hopf-Galois extensions obtained by  repeatedly attaching an ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-cell. This construction should be compared to Lazard's construction of the Lazard ring in \cite{laz}. Antolin-Camarena and Barthel also have ongoing work applying these concepts to the $p$-complete Hopf-Galois extension $H{\mathbb{Z}}^\wedge_p\to H{\mathbb{Z}}/p$. 

\begin{cor}
Let $X(n)$ be the Thom spectrum associated to the morphism of ${\mathbb{E}}_2$-monoidal Kan complexes $\Omega {\mathrm{SU}}(n)\to {B\mathrm{U}}\to BGL_1({\mathbb{S}})$. Then $X(n+1)$ is a versal ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-algebra over $X(n)$ of characteristic $\overset{\smallfrown}\chi_n$ where $\{\overset{\smallfrown}\chi_{n}\}_{{\mathbb{N}}}$ is a canonical sequence of elements in $\pi_{2n-1}(X(n))$. 
\end{cor}

\begin{proof}
Given the fibration $\Omega {\mathrm{SU}}(n)\to\Omega {\mathrm{SU}}(n+1)\to \Omega S^{2n+1}$, and by an application of Theorem \ref{mainthm} and Lemma \ref{fibs} above we can identify $X(n+1)$ as the ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-monoidal Thom spectrum given by the ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-monoidal left Kan extension $\Omega S^{2n+1}\to BGL_1(X(n))$. The map of ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-monoidal Kan complexes $\chi_n\in Map_{{\mathbb{E}}_1}(\Omega S^{2n+1},BGL_1(X(n)))$, by application of standard adjunctions, induces a map of Kan complexes $\tilde{\chi}_n\in Map_{{\mathcal{T}}}(S^{2n-1},GL_1(X(n)))$. Note that $\tilde{\chi}_n$ must have image contained in a connected component $u\in\pi_0(GL_1(X(n))\simeq{\mathbb{Z}}/2$ which induces a translation $\tau_u:\Omega^\infty X(n)\to\Omega^\infty X(n)$. The composition $\tau_u\circ\tilde{\chi}_n:S^{2n-1}\to \Omega^\infty X(n)$ lifts to a morphism of spectra $\overset{\smallfrown}{\chi}_n:{\mathbb{S}}^{2n-1}\to X(n)$. An application of Theorem 4.10 of \cite{acb} gives that $X(n+1)$ is the versal ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-algebra of characteristic $\overset{\smallfrown}{\chi}_n$ on $X(n)$. 
\end{proof}

\begin{rem}
The content of \cite{acb} allows us to consider $X(n+1)$ as the ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-spectrum obtained by attaching an ${\mathbb{E}}_1$-cell to $X(n)$ along the map $\overset{\smallfrown}{\chi}_n$ described above. Note that $\overset{\smallfrown}{\chi}_1\simeq \eta$, the Hopf element in $\pi_1({\mathbb{S}})$. 
\end{rem}

